<figureCitation box="[1069,1137,848,874]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionTargetBox="[345,1238,1442,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[345,1243,1434,1909]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 3. Female terminalia. A. Ectophasiopsis gradata (Wiedemann, 1830) comb. nov. B. E. ypiranga sp. nov. Abbreviations: C = Cerci; s7 = Sternite 7; s8 = Sternite 8. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3829850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3829850/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A–B), or cerci widely separated basally with converging apical portions elongate and slender, forceps-like (subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berthold" authorityYear="1827" box="[234,369,920,946]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Trichopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[234,369,920,946]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trichopoda</emphasis>
